{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521092"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13548"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13548"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.34,0.1,0.47,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84682"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6163"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13548"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2305"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"3632"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44393"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84682"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man was brought in by his family to the Emergency Department due to altered behaviour, headache, and fever over the past week. Medical history is significant for Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) infection with suboptimal adherence to clinic follow-up and treatment. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. He is confused and has nuchal rigidity. Neuroimaging showed leptomeningeal enhancement. Lumbar puncture is performed and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) sent for analysis. The results are given below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOpening pressure: 25 cmH2O (6-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMacroscopic appearance: turbid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose: 1 mmol/L (2.5-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein: 0.7 g/L (0.15-0.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeucocyte count: 23 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L, 98% mononuclear cells (\u0026lt;5 mononuclear cells)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythrocyte count: 0 x10\u003Csup\u003E6\u003C/sup\u003E/L (\u0026lt;1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicroscopy, gram stain, culture and PCR panel are pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebral toxoplasmosis","Neisseria meningitidis meningitis","Herpes simplex virus type 1 encephalitis","Cryptococcal meningitis","Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms of headache, fever, altered mental status, and nuchal rigidity are consistent with meningitis. In addition, lumbar puncture may show an elevated opening pressure. The typical cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) changes seen in different types of infections are compared in Table 1 (Image 1). However, it is important to note that these changes are variable and the definitive diagnosis requires identification of the pathogen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor individuals living with HIV who present with symptoms and signs of a central nervous system (CNS) infection, \u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcal meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral toxoplasmosis\u003C/strong\u003E are important differentials to consider. The risk is highest in individuals with CD4 count of \u0026lt;100 cells/mm^3. These are Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS)-defining conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcal meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the CSF and neuroimaging findings. It is caused by \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/em\u003E, transmitted by avian excreta which contaminates soil. CSF findings may be abnormal as summarised in Table 1. Neuroimaging may show leptomeningeal enhancement and hydrocephalus but typically does not show any space-occupying lesions. The diagnosis can be confirmed using a cryptococcal antigen immunoassay, which is more commonly performed than India ink stain nowadays.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral toxoplasmosis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/em\u003E, transmitted by feline faeces. Neuroimaging typically shows multiple ring-enhancing lesions which is not consistent with this case. A positive toxoplasma serology also supports the diagnosis in patients with compatible clinical and neuroimaging features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn bacterial meningitis (e.g., \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E), CSF typically shows neutrophilic leucocytosis rather than predominance of lymphocytes. In viral meningitis (e.g., \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHerpes simplex virus type 1\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E), CSF typically shows mildly elevated protein and normal glucose. Hence, these diagnoses are not as likely based on the CSF findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a demyelinating disease of the CNS caused by the John Cunningham virus, typically seen in immunocompromised patients. It presents with progressive neurological deficits rather than meningitic symptoms, and CSF analysis is typically non-specific. Neuroimaging typically shows multifocal demyelinating lesions which is not consistent with this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cryptococcal meningitis, caused by Cryptococcus neoformans, is an AIDS-defining condition in individuals living with HIV.","CSF findings in cryptococcal meningitis typically show elevated opening pressure, low glucose, elevated protein, and lymphocytic pleocytosis.","Cryptococcal antigen testing of CSF is the preferred diagnostic test for cryptococcal meningitis."],"references":["Shahan B, Choi EY, Nieves G. Cerebrospinal Fluid Analysis. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Apr 1;103(7):422-428. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2021/0401/p422.html","Williamson PR, Jarvis JN, Panackal AA, Fisher MC, Molloy SF, Loyse A, et al. Cryptococcal meningitis: epidemiology, immunology, diagnosis and therapy. Nature Reviews Neurology. 2016 Nov 25;13(1):13\u201324. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27886201/","\u200cTugume L, Ssebambulidde K, Kasibante J, Ellis J, Wake RM, Gakuru J, et al. Cryptococcal meningitis. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2023 Nov 9;9(1):1\u201318. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41572-023-00472-z","Elsheikha HM, Marra CM, Zhu XQ. Epidemiology, Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Management of Cerebral Toxoplasmosis. Clinical Microbiology Reviews. 2020 Nov 25;34(1):10.1128/cmr.00115-19. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33239310/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13548"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20938"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20938"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d1QIiog610rxXDQYzqcn0PNb8IjDRd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d1QIiog610rxXDQYzqcn0PNb8IjDRd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1222,"height":712}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T11:19:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T11:19:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6163"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84682"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"